       <article class="post-841 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-general category-policy tag-congress tag-policy">
        <header>
         <h2 class="title entry-title">
          <a href="http://policymatters.illinois.edu/drinking-from-the-well-of-political-thought-part-1/" rel="bookmark" title="Drinking from the Well of Political Thought, Part 1">
           Drinking from the Well of Political Thought, Part 1
          </a>
         </h2>
        </header>
        <div class="post-meta">
         <span class="small">
          By
         </span>
         <a class="author url fn" href="http://policymatters.illinois.edu/author/jcoppess/" rel="author" title="Posts by Jonathan Coppess">
          Jonathan Coppess
         </a>
         <span class="small">
          on
         </span>
         <abbr class="date time published updated" title="2018-03-16T14:55:33+0000">
          March 16, 2018
         </abbr>
         <span class="small">
          in
         </span>
         <span class="categories">
          <a href="http://policymatters.illinois.edu/category/general/" title="View all items in General">
           General
          </a>
          ,
          <a href="http://policymatters.illinois.edu/category/policy/" title="View all items in Policy">
           Policy
          </a>
         </span>
        </div>
        <section class="entry">
         <p>
          These are challenging times for policy; intense partisan and ideological polarization pervades the land, serving to confound the policies that should connect citizens and shaking confidence in the representatives elected to craft them. A recent poll found that 85 percent of Americans disapprove of the job Congress is doing; two-in-ten people think Congress fails to […]
         </p>
        </section>
        <!-- /.entry -->
